  "prompt": "What's the difference between an appositive and subject compliment?",
  "response": "An appositive and a subject complement are both grammatical constructs, but they serve different functions in a sentence.\n\n### Appositive\nAn appositive is a noun or noun phrase that renames or provides additional information about another noun next to it. It usually follows the noun it describes and is often set off by commas if it\u2019s non-restrictive (providing extra information that isn\u2019t essential to identify the noun).\n\n**Example:** \n- My brother, **a talented musician**, plays the guitar. \n  (Here, \"a talented musician\" is an appositive that gives more information about \"my brother.\")\n\n### Subject Complement\nA subject complement is a word or phrase (often a noun, pronoun, or adjective) that follows a linking verb and provides additional information about the subject of the sentence. It can be a predicate nominative (a noun or pronoun) or a predicate adjective (an adjective describing the subject).\n\n**Example:** \n- My brother is **a talented musician**. \n  (In this sentence, \"a talented musician\" is a subject complement that renames the subject \"my brother.\")\n\nIn summary, the key differences are:\n- An appositive renames or provides extra information about a noun but does not necessarily follow a verb. It can stand alone.\n- A subject complement follows a linking verb and is used to complete the meaning of the subject.",
